<paragraph blockId="57.[189,1399,708,1029]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[320,408,708,734]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Galapa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[320,408,708,734]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Galapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was established for two species endemic to the 
<collectingRegion box="[981,1196,708,734]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Galapagos Islands</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Huber B. A." box="[1212,1360,708,734]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref127973" refString="Huber B. A. 2000. New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 254: 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 % 3 C 0001: NWPSAP % 3 E 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
). A third species was described in 2014, also from the 
<collectingRegion box="[775,988,745,771]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Galapagos Islands</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Baert L." box="[1003,1138,745,771]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="263 - 271" refId="ref126061" refString="Baert L. 2014. New spider species (Araneae) from the Galapagos Islands (Ecuador). Bulletin de la Societe royale belge d'Entomologie 149: 263 - 271." type="journal article" year="2014">Baert 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The new Venezuelan species below is assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[547,635,782,808]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Galapa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[547,635,782,808]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Galapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because it shares two specific similarities: (1) unique (among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1890" box="[189,305,819,846]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ninetinae">Ninetinae</taxonomicName>
) armature of the male chelicerae (processes on male cheliceral fangs but otherwise unmodified; compare 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber B. A." box="[299,444,856,882]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref127973" refString="Huber B. A. 2000. New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 254: 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 % 3 C 0001: NWPSAP % 3 E 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 384 and 
<figureCitation box="[609,712,856,882]" captionStart="Figs 178–182" captionStartId="59.[189,241,1780,1806]" captionTargetBox="[192,1392,289,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-82@59.[189,1398,289,1718]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Figs 178–182. Galapa spiniphila Huber sp. nov.; from Falcón, near Cueva del Guano (type locality; ZFMK Ar 21860). 178–179. Left male pedipalp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 180. Left procursus and genital bulb, dorsal view. 181. Male ocular area, clypeus, and chelicerae, frontal view (arrow: process on male cheliceral fang). 182. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: b= genital bulb; p=procursus. Scale lines: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4069648" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4069648/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 181</figureCitation>
); (2) dorsal (in the new species below slightly prolateral) process of the procursus (compare 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber B. A." box="[609,754,892,919]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref127973" refString="Huber B. A. 2000. New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 254: 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 % 3 C 0001: NWPSAP % 3 E 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
: figs 383, 387 with 
<figureCitation box="[994,1098,892,919]" captionStart="Figs 178–182" captionStartId="59.[189,241,1780,1806]" captionTargetBox="[192,1392,289,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-82@59.[189,1398,289,1718]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Figs 178–182. Galapa spiniphila Huber sp. nov.; from Falcón, near Cueva del Guano (type locality; ZFMK Ar 21860). 178–179. Left male pedipalp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 180. Left procursus and genital bulb, dorsal view. 181. Male ocular area, clypeus, and chelicerae, frontal view (arrow: process on male cheliceral fang). 182. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: b= genital bulb; p=procursus. Scale lines: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4069648" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4069648/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 180</figureCitation>
). In addition, the general morphology of the proximal palpal segments is similar (slender femur, large tibia), and the genital bulb of the new species below strongly resembles the bulb of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gertsch &amp; Peck, 1992)" baseAuthorityName="Gertsch &amp; Peck" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[875,1278,966,993]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Galapa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="baerti">
<emphasis box="[875,983,966,993]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">G. baerti</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gertsch W. J. &amp; Peck S. B." box="[1001,1270,966,992]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="1185 - 1199" refId="ref127074" refString="Gertsch W. J. &amp; Peck S. B. 1992. The pholcid spiders of the Galapagos Islands, Ecuador (Araneae: Pholcidae). Canadian Journal of Zoology 70: 1185 - 1199. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / z 92 - 166" type="journal article" year="1992">Gertsch &amp; Peck, 1992</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(compare 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber B. A." box="[189,333,1003,1029]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref127973" refString="Huber B. A. 2000. New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 254: 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 % 3 C 0001: NWPSAP % 3 E 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 381 with 
<figureCitation box="[500,602,1003,1029]" captionStart="Figs 178–182" captionStartId="59.[189,241,1780,1806]" captionTargetBox="[192,1392,289,1696]" captionTargetId="figure-82@59.[189,1398,289,1718]" captionTargetPageId="59" captionText="Figs 178–182. Galapa spiniphila Huber sp. nov.; from Falcón, near Cueva del Guano (type locality; ZFMK Ar 21860). 178–179. Left male pedipalp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 180. Left procursus and genital bulb, dorsal view. 181. Male ocular area, clypeus, and chelicerae, frontal view (arrow: process on male cheliceral fang). 182. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: b= genital bulb; p=procursus. Scale lines: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4069648" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4069648/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 178</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[189,1399,1070,1243]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
This suggests that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[407,495,1070,1096]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Galapa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[407,495,1070,1096]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Galapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may in fact be a widespread genus. An undescribed species from 
<collectingCountry box="[1270,1399,1070,1096]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[197,337,1107,1133]" country="Costa Rica" name="Guanacaste" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Guanacaste</collectingRegion>
, no precise locality data; deposited in ZFMK) may also belong in this group and thus support this view. It seems to lack a dorsal process on the procursus but shares the unique cheliceral morphology and is also otherwise very similar. A formal test of the monophyly of the genus does 
<taxonomicName box="[1361,1398,1181,1207]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="57" pageNumber="241" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
exist.
</paragraph>
